a Pradesh]]: 4,457\n|-\n| [[Uttarakhand]]: 759\n|-\n| [[Uttar Pradesh]]: 8,929\n|-\n!Western region: 29,633\n|-\n| [[Goa]]: 77\n|-\n| [[Gujarat]]: 8,154\n|-\n| [[Maharashtra]]: 21,402\n|-\n!Southern region: 13,703\n|-\n| [[Andhra Pradesh]]: 2,808\n|-\n| [[Karnataka]]: 4,740\n|-\n| [[Kerala]]: 1,566\n|-\n| [[Puducherry]]: 53\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu]]: 4,538\n|-\n| [[Telangana]] : 0\n|-\n!Total in all India: 92,432\n|-\n|}\n<ref>[http://rbidocs.rbi.org.in/rdocs/Publications/PDFs/506APPT211113.pdf   PACS- rbi ] RBI</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://m.businesstoday.in/story/labour-law-reforms-no-one-knows-actual-size-india-informal-workforce-not-even-govt/1/364361.html\n\n[[Category:Agricultural finance in India]]\n[[Category:Cooperative banks of India]]\n[[Category:Government-owned banks of India]]\n", "name_user": "Manjinder3770", "label": "safe", "comment": "add desire links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_Agricultural_Credit_Society"}
{"title_page": "Australian railway signalling", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n'''Australian railway signalling''' varies between the states of [[Australia]] as each railway was established under the different [[Colony|colonial]] [[Government|governments]] with separate legislation. As with the notorious situation of having different gauges, there are differing signal systems. [[New South Wales]] [[Railway signalling|signalling systems]] generally follow [[British Empire|British]] precepts, however American influence has increased somewhat since the 1990s. The [[Victorian Railways]] use [https://signalbox.org/overseas/australia/speed.htm ''Speed Signalling''.] This can cause confusion where the systems meet. For example, in [[New South Wales]], [[Green]]-over-Red means 'Caution', indicating the next signal is at 'Stop'. In [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] that same aspect, Green-over-Red, means 'Clear Normal Speed', indicating the next signal is anything but at 'Stop'. On the main south line from [[Sydney]], Single Light Colour Light signals are now exclusively used from Spring Creek bridge (south of [[Galong railway station|Galong]]) to [[Albury railway station|Albury]] on the [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] border. This forms a buffer zone between the areas giving conflicting signal indications. Gradually the remaining [[Railway semaphore signal|Upper Quadrant signals]] (and Double Light Colour Light signals at Binalong) are being replaced by Single Light [[Colour]] Light signals.\n\n[[Rail transport in South Australia|South Australia]] uses two primary forms of signalling. Nearly all [[signal box]]es in [[South Australia]] have now been closed, and most rail traffic is coordinated through [[Centralized traffic control|centralised traffic control]] systems, either under [[Australian Rail Track Corporation]] control from Mile End or [[Adelaide Metro]] control from [[Adelaide]].<ref>[[Adelaide|Adelaide as a tourist place]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}} Where these two networks interface, such as at the [[Goodwood railway station|Goodwood level crossing]] or at Torrens Junction, control is usually from [[Australian Rail Track Corporation|ARTC]] after release from Adelaide Metro. The [[Western Australian]] system is very simple to understand but the complexities of [[leading]] position lights and other odd [[wikt:attachment|attachment]]s to signalling [[wikt:apparatus|apparatus]] have been either eradicated or were never part of it. Switchlocks are used to exit mainline [[Centralized traffic control|CTC]] territory for sidings, such as CBH yard [[terminal]]s{{dn|date=April 2020}} on the Standard Gauge. The Train Controller must release the switchlock thus [[interlocking]] the signals to stop and this is similar to [[Queensland]]. [[Perth|Perth's]] urban passenger network is operated by the [[Public Transport Authority (Western Australia)|Public Transport Authority]] and the Rules are identical to that of the [[Freight transport|freight]], with a few minor differences.\n\n== Overall Signalling Comparison ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Table comparing the main aspects of each states system to show similar aspect meanings. \nSee individual states for more information and clarification.\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Standard Name\n! colspan=\"2\" |NSW\n! rowspan=\"2\" |QLD\n! colspan=\"2\" |VIC\n! colspan=\"2\" |SA\n! rowspan=\"2\" |WA\n|-\n!Double\nColour\n!Single\nColour\n!Two\nAspect\n!Three\nAspect\n!Route\n!Speed\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" |'''Main Aspects'''\n|-\n|Clear\n|Proceed, expect the next signal to be at Clear\n|[[File:Sydney_Double_Colour_Signalling_Clear_Aspect.png|alt=|frameless|76x76px]]\n|[[File:NSWR Green.png|frameless|82x82px]]\n|[[File:Proceed_QLD.png|frameless|78x78px]]\n|[[File:VIC_2_Aspect_Green.png|frameless|87x87px]]\n|[[File:Melbourne_Green_Signal_Searchlight.png|frameless|82x82px]]\n|[[File:Proceed_QLD.png|frameless|83x83px]]\n|[[File:SA_green.png|frameless|88x88px]]\